 This is the procedural script for  mini project on topic : 'CRISPR guide RNA design'

Step 1 : Selecting the suitable gene from NCBI database
- I have chosen the AMR gene mecA, which is responsible for the methicillin resistance. 
- I selected mecA from Streptococcus pyogenes with Gene ID: 69900206
- Download the Gene sequence in FASTA format by selecting the menu download datasets and the
  mark the Gene sequence (FASTA), then download the file named mecA_datasets.zip.
- Extract the file and rename the gene as mecA_gene. 

Step 2 : Loading the mecA_gene to preinstalled SnapGene Viewer software
- If you are unable to directly load into snapgene. 
- Do this instead. Right click on the file mecA_gene, select edit in notepad option and then copy it and 
  paste in the create the DNA sequence box 
  (Prior to that in snapgene click on file --> Create new DNA file --> Creating the following sequence)
- It will show a DNA map in linear or circular format based on your selected option. 
- Now in the bottom there are many options like map, sequence, enzyme and so on. In that opt for 'Sequence', 
  select the gene sequences (ATGC....) by draging your mouse. 

Step 3 : Open CHOPCHOP in browser
(i) Loading the sequence to CHOPCHOP interface
- After opening the CHOPCHOP, click on the menu paste target which will changes to Gene target. 
  Now paste your copied sequence (from snapgene) into the 'target' box. 
- Then next to the target box there is 'In' box, type your selected organism name (Streptococcus pyogenes). 
  For 'Using' box click on CRISPR/Cas9, then for last box ('for') select activation. Now select the 'Options', 
  in that select Cas9 and also check for PAM3' sequence as NGG or else and also the gRNA length of 20bp, 
  apart from this leave other features as default. Finally click on Find Target Sites!
  After awhile it will give results. 
- Roadmap : 
  Browser -> CHOPCHOP -> Paste -> target -> Target -> In -> Using -> For -> Options --> Find Target Sites!

(ii) Analysing the Result;
- The CHOPCHOP will gives many target sequences in the form of table having rank, genomic location, strand, 
  GC content, efficiecny, self complementary,  mismatches (MM0, MM1, MM2) and a visual map at the top. 
- Now you have to click on dropdown named as 'Please select one' (Download results). 
  In that opt for "Results table as .tsv" , it will downloads the result. 
- After downloading, right click on result file and select edit in notepad, 
  copy the whole table content (Ctrl+A)and paste it to new excel sheet.

Step 4 : Filtering in Excel
- After pasting the tsv file into the excel. Expand the sequence column, so that complete nucleotides 
  are visible and feasible for further work.
- Select the first row (i.e., Headings), then click on Home tab and 
  in editing ribbon select Sort & Filter, click 'filter'
- Now click on the small dropdown seeing on rightside of each of the column heading and optimise the values. 
- We usually set following parameters which has already been standardized by scientist and industrial peoples.
  a) Efficiency - >50 % 
  b) Self complementary - 0
  c) GC content - 40 - 60%
  d) Mismatches
- After doing this filter step, we are left with few target gene options. In this we have to select each 
  target seq and paste it to SnapGene viewer to see if it is there or not.
- The filtered results gave me only two target sequences - TTGATTGAGCATGCAAACCCTGG and TTCAACGATTACAGAGGCAGTGG

Step 5 : Annotating in SnapGene viewer
- Press Ctrl+F, which opens a dialogue box in bottom and there paste your copied target sequence (taken from
  Excel), hit enter.
- Now the target gene will be shown in the linear sequence
- See the NGG and select it --> Features --> add feature (Ctrl+T)--> change the color --> rename it to PAM --> OK
  This visually differentiate from other sequence. 
- Select the remaining 20 bp in the target and follow above step, but rename it to Guide_cas9, also select the
  direction arrow to showcase the working of cas9 enzyme.
- This way you can also design gRNA for cas12a and cas12b which are of diagnostic importance. 
